'''Bosseopentaenoic acid (BPA)''' is a [[conjugated system|conjugated]] [[polyunsaturated fatty acid]]. Bosseopentaenoic acid can be extracted from the red [[coralline alga]]e, ''[[Bossiella]] orbigniana''.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Burgess, J.R. |author2=De la Rosa, R.I. |author3=Jacobs, R.S. |author4=Butler, A |title= A new eicosapentaenoic acid formed from arachidonic acid in the coralline red algae ''Bossiella orbigniana''|journal = Lipids |volume = 26 |issue=2 |pages=1057–1059| doi=10.1007/BF02544012| year=1991}}</ref> The first total synthesis of methyl bosseopentaenoate by consecutive palladium-catalyzed reactions was reported in 2011.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Mohamed, Y. M. A. |author2=Hansen, T. V. |year= 2011 |title= Synthesis of methyl-(5''Z'',8''Z'',10''E'',12''E'',14''Z'')-eicosapentaenoate |journal= Tetrahedron Letters |volume= 52 |issue= 10 |pages= 1057–1059 |doi= 10.1016/j.tetlet.2010.12.078 }}</ref> In 2017, bosseopentaenoic acid was obtained from the ester hydrolysis of methyl bosseopentaenoate in good yield using mild condition and the synthesis of its sulfur-bridged analogue of BPA; thiophene analogue was achieved by Mohamed and Solum <ref>{{cite journal| author1= Mohamed, Y. M. A. |author2= Solum, E. J.|year= 2017| volume=2017| issue= part v|title= An efficient stereoselective synthesis of a sulfur-bridged analogue of bosseopentaenoic acid as a potential antioxidant agent| journal = Arkivoc|pages=10-19|doi= 10.24820/ark.5550190.p010.086}}</ref> In this study, a comparison between the thiophene analogue and BPA with respect to their antioxidant activity was accomplished. It was shown that the rigidified analogue; the thiophene analogue exhibited higher free radical scavenging potential than the bosseopentaenoic acid. The results showed that by lowering the flexibility of the BPA as [[lead compound]] by incorporation thiophene ring in its structure, an increased antioxidant activity was observed. This study opens the door to investigate the relationship between the flexibility of other [[polyunsaturated fatty acids]] (PUFAs) and enhancement in the biological activity. ==References== <references/>
